1. # **Project Overview**

This application enables real-time communication between registered users. Core features include user registration and authentication, sending and receiving text messages or images, and maintaining secure user sessions. The system supports real-time interaction through WebSockets, ensuring seamless communication within the platform. Registered users can also change the website's wallpaper/theme.

2. # **Technologies Used**

The application was developed using the MERN stack (MongoDB, Express.js, React.js, Node.js). In addition to the core technologies, the following libraries and tools were utilized:

**Frontend:**

* **DaisyUI** – For prebuilt Tailwind CSS components.  
* **React Hot Toast** – For toast notifications.  
* **React Icons** – To add icon sets.  
* **React DOM** – For DOM rendering in React.  
* **Tailwind CSS** – For utility-first CSS styling.  
* **Lucide-React** – For modern SVG icons.  
* **Autoprefixer** – For handling browser-specific CSS prefixes.  
* **ESLint** – For code linting and ensuring code quality.  
* **Vite** – As a fast development server and bundler.  
* **Framer Motion \-** For UI animation

**Backend:**

* **Bcrypt** – For hashing and verifying passwords.  
* **Cloudinary** – For uploading and storing media files (e.g., images).  
* **Cookie-Parser** – For parsing cookies in requests.  
* **CORS** – To handle cross-origin requests.  
* **Dotenv** – For environment variable management.  
* **JSON Web Token (JWT)** – For user authentication and session handling.  
* **Mongoos**e – For MongoDB object modeling.  
* **Nodemon** – For automatic server restarts during development.  
* **Socket.io** – For real-time, bidirectional communication between client and server.

**AI:**

* **ChatGPT \-** For easier debugging

3. # **Setup Instructions**

**Step-by-Step Guide:**

**1\. Clone the Repository:**

git clone https://github.com/beejq/taram-chat-app

**2\. Install Dependencies:**  
Navigate to the frontend and backend folders separately and run:

npm install

**3\. Set Environment Variables:**  
Create a .env file in the backend folder and add:

MONGO\_URI=your\_mongodb\_connection\_string  
JWT\_SECRET=your\_jwt\_secret  
CLOUDINARY\_CLOUD\_NAME=your\_cloud\_name  
CLOUDINARY\_API\_KEY=your\_api\_key  
CLOUDINARY\_API\_SECRET=your\_api\_secret

**4\. Run the Application:**

**Go to Backend Folder and:**

npm run dev

**Go to Frontend Folder and:**

npm run dev

5. # **Code Explanation**

**Backend:**

API Routes:

Authentication Routes:

router.post("/signup", signup); //Creating account  
router.post("/login", login); //Logging in account  
router.post("/logout", logout); //Logging out account

//Before updating profile, protectRoute verifies if user has a token, after verifying updateProfile is called (Changing profile picture)  
router.put("/update-profile", protectRoute, updateProfile);

//Checking Authenticated Users  
router.get("/check", protectRoute, checkAuth)

Message Routes:

router.get("/users", protectRoute, getUsersForSidebar); //Getting all registered users  
router.get("/:id", protectRoute, getMessages); //Getting all messages

router.post("/send/:id", protectRoute, sendMessage); //Sending message to a specific user

Models:

User Model:

const userSchema \= new mongoose.Schema(  
    {  
        email: {  
            type: String,  
            required: true,  
            unique: true,  
        },  
        fullName: {  
            type: String,  
            required: true,  
        },  
        password: {  
            type: String,  
            required: true,  
            minlength: 6,  
        },  
        profilePic: {  
            type: String,  
            default: "",  
        },

    },  
    { timestamps: true }  
);

Message Model:

const messageSchema \= new mongoose.Schema(  
    {  
        senderId: {  
            type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId, //tells mongoDB that this is a reference to the User model  
            ref: "User",  
            required: true,  
        },  
        receiverId: {  
            type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId, //tells mongoDB that this is a reference to the User model  
            ref: "User",  
            required: true,  
        },  
        text: {  
            type: String,  
        },  
        image: {  
            type: String,  
        },  
    },  
    { timestamps: true }  
);

Middleware:

- protectRoute basically tries to get a user's token if they have one, else they are unauthorized. If they have a token, it must be verified first, and then after that, find that specific user with that token.

export const protectRoute \= *async* (req , res , next) \=\> {  
    try {  
        const token \= req.cookies.jwt;

        if(\!token){  
            return res.status(401).json({ message: "Unauthorized \- No Token Provided" });  
        };

        const decoded \= jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT\_SECRET);

        if(\!decoded) {  
            return res.status(401).json({message: "Unauthorized \- Invalid Token"});  
        };

        const user \= await User.findById(decoded.userId).select("-password");

        if(\!user) {  
            return res.status(404).json({message: "User not found"});  
        }

        req.user \= user

        next();

    } catch (error) {  
        console.log("Error in protectRoute middleware: ", error.message);  
        return res.status(500).json({message: "Internal Server Error"});  
    }  
}

**Frontend:**

**React Components:**

* **ChatContainer** \- area for messages (chat bubbles)  
* **ChatHeader** \- area for the user information of the selected user for the chat container  
* **MessageInput \-** area for typing a message /  uploading an image, and sending it  
* **Navbar \-** navigation bar  
* **NoChatSelected \-** shown when a user has no selected user to chat with  
* **Sidebar \-** area for showing online and offline users, also online only filter button  
* **ThemeContext \-** for changing theme and wallpaper  
* **Skeletons** \- placeholder for users and messages while the actual ones are still loading

**State Management:**

* **useTheme():** Manages the application's theme. It toggles between themes based on user interaction, such as clicking on a wallpaper.

* **useAuthStore()**: Handles authentication-related state. It checks if a user is authenticated, tracks online users, and triggers toast notifications for actions like logging in, signing up, logging out, sending messages, and updating the profile.

* **useChatStore():** Manages chat-related state, including storing messages, setting active users, and handling sending/receiving messages.

**API Calls:**

**getUsers:** /api/auth/messages/users  
const res \= await axiosInstance.get("/messages/users");

**getMessages**: /api/auth/messages/:id  
const res \= await axiosInstance.get(\`/messages/${userId}\`);

**sendMessage**: /api/auth/messages/send/:id   
const res \= await axiosInstance.post(\`/messages/send/${selectedUser.\_id}\`,messageData);

**checkAuth**: /api/auth/check  
const res \= await axiosInstance.get("/auth/check");

**signup**: /api/auth/signup  
const res \= await axiosInstance.post("/auth/signup", data);

**login**: /api/auth/login  
const res \= await axiosInstance.post("/auth/login", data);

**logout**: /api/auth/logout  
await axiosInstance.post("/auth/logout");

**updateProfile**: /api/auth/update-profile  
const res \= await axiosInstance.put("/auth/update-profile", data);

	Many challenges were faced during the creation of this project. Sometimes, some bugs took me longer than expected to fix, and sometimes it would just be issues such as failing to import, misspelled words, wrong syntax, and more. Modifying the styling of the application to make it more personalized and according to the design I created made it challenging; some styling didn’t work, and I had a hard time incorporating Tailwind CSS, as it was my first time using it, and I was just getting used to using vanilla CSS. Understanding some parts of the video was also hard for me to understand, as it felt overwhelming. Deploying was also hard, as I had an error that I couldn’t fix, and was only able to fix it due to a YouTube comment.

9. # **Deployment**

**Live Link: [Taram](https://taram-chat-app.onrender.com/login)**

1. Go to the root folder and run in the terminal: npm init \-y to get package.json  
2. In the package.json file, add under the scripts  
   1. "build":"npm install \--prefix backend && npm install \--prefix frontend && npm run build \--prefix frontend",  
   2.  "start":"npm run start \--prefix backend"

3. Go to the backend folder and inside the package.json file add under the scripts  
   1.  "start": "node src/index.js"

4. Go to backend folder and visit [index.](http://index.js)js and import path  
   	import path from "path";  
5. And add  
   if(process.env.NODE\_ENV==="production"){  
       app.use(express.static(path.join(\_\_dirname, "../frontend/dist")));  
     
       app.get("\*", (req, res) \=\> {  
           res.sendFile(path.join(\_\_dirname, "../frontend", "dist", "index.html"));  
       })  
   }

6. Visit [https://dashboard.render.com/](https://dashboard.render.com/)  
7. Click New and Web Service  
8. Click the GitHub repository for the web application  
9. Under Build Command add: npm run build  
10. Under Start Command add: npm run start  
11. Choose an Instance Type  
12. For the Environment Variables  
    1. Go to your .env file and copy from it, and paste it into Render  
13. Click Deploy Service and wait  
14. Click the live link for the deployed website: [Taram](https://taram-chat-app.onrender.com/login)
